<h2>Market Opportunity</h2>

<p>Prepped sits at the intersection of three large and growing global markets: meal kit delivery, catering services, and restaurant management software.</p>

<h3>Meal Kit & Meal Prep</h3>
<p>The global meal kit delivery market was valued at <strong>$39.4 billion in 2025</strong> and is projected to reach <strong>$79.8 billion by 2033</strong> at an 8.4% CAGR (Grand View Research). The broader prepared meals category — which includes meal prep operators serving corporate clients, gyms, and households — reaches <strong>$190 billion in 2025</strong>, growing toward $326 billion by 2034 (Fortune Business Insights). There are currently 21+ million meal kit users globally, growing annually.</p>

<h3>Catering Management Software</h3>
<p>The catering management software market is valued at <strong>$1 billion in 2024</strong>, projected to reach <strong>$2.84 billion by 2033</strong> at a 12.3% CAGR (Straits Research). The broader cloud-based catering software segment reaches <strong>$1.8 billion in 2024</strong>, growing to <strong>$5.6 billion by 2033</strong> at a 13.4% CAGR. This software layer serves a global catering services industry valued at <strong>$154.7 billion in 2024</strong>, projected to reach $229.9 billion by 2033 (IMARC Group).</p>

<h3>Restaurant & Food Service Technology</h3>
<p>Restaurant management software — the broader category that encompasses Prepped's feature set — is a <strong>$6.54 billion market in 2025</strong>, growing to <strong>$13 billion by 2030</strong> at a <strong>14.74% CAGR</strong> (Mordor Intelligence). Cloud-based deployments now represent 60.9% of the market, growing at 14.9% annually. Small chains of 2–20 locations show the strongest adoption growth at 15.78% CAGR — precisely the customer profile Prepped serves.</p>

<h3>International Growth Rates</h3>
<p>Growth outside North America consistently outpaces the global average across all three markets. Asia-Pacific holds <strong>42% of global restaurant management software revenue in 2025</strong> and is growing at a <strong>16.24% CAGR</strong> — the fastest of any region (Mordor Intelligence). Latin American restaurant software is growing at <strong>16.4% CAGR</strong>. The GCC (Gulf Cooperation Council) region is growing at <strong>17.5% CAGR</strong>, driven by booming hospitality sectors in the UAE and Saudi Arabia. Japan ranks second globally for meal kit revenue at $1.68 billion; the UK ranks third at $1.4 billion; Australia's meal kit market is growing rapidly toward $570 million.</p>

<h2>The Problem</h2>

<p>Meal prep is a high-growth industry built on manual operations. A typical small operator takes orders via Instagram DMs or Google Forms, tracks them in spreadsheets, calculates production needs by hand, and coordinates deliveries through text messages. This works at 20 orders a week. At 200 it breaks. At 2,000 it is impossible.</p>

<p>Generic e-commerce platforms handle the ordering piece but nothing downstream. They don't generate production reports, calculate ingredient quantities across recipes, manage rotating subscriptions where customers select different meals each week, or coordinate delivery routes. Meal prep and catering businesses need vertical software that understands their entire workflow — not just the checkout page.</p>

<p>This gap exists equally in Melbourne, Manchester, Mexico City, and Minneapolis. The operational problem is universal. The lack of purpose-built tooling is universal. Prepped addresses both.</p>

<h2>Revenue Model</h2>

<p>Transaction-based pricing that scales with the vendor's business. No monthly minimums, no annual contracts, no upfront costs.</p>

<h3>Starter — 3.5% + $0.50 per order</h3>
<p>For businesses processing fewer than 100 orders per month. Includes the complete <a href="https://orderprepped.com" rel="noopener noreferrer">meal prep software</a>, payment integration, menu and recipe management, and production reports with labels. This tier is designed for new food businesses that need professional infrastructure without capital risk.</p>

<h3>Growth — 1.5% + $0.30 per order</h3>
<p>For businesses processing 100+ orders per month. Adds advanced analytics and forecasting, custom branding and domain, priority support, and API access. A business doing 500 orders per month at this tier pays roughly $900/month — a fraction of what custom software or a full-time operations hire would cost at that scale.</p>

<h3>Enterprise — Custom pricing</h3>
<p>For multi-location operations and large-scale caterers. Includes a dedicated account manager, white-label platform and mobile app, custom integrations, and SLA guarantees. This tier serves operators with compliance, branding isolation, or POS integration requirements.</p>

<h2>Platform Features</h2>

<h3>Subscription Engine</h3>
<p>The subscription system handles both fixed recurring orders and rotating subscriptions where customers select different products each cycle. Customers can pause, skip individual delivery slots, or adjust selections — all self-service. At the cutoff time for each cycle, the system automatically generates orders, calculates production requirements, and queues fulfillment. The engine operates correctly across timezones, making it equally viable for operators in any global market.</p>

<h3>Production Workflows</h3>
<p>This is where Prepped diverges most sharply from generic e-commerce. The platform aggregates all orders for a production window, calculates total ingredient quantities across recipes, generates shopping lists, creates production schedules with batch sequencing, and prints shipping labels. A meal prep company producing 500 meals doesn't manually cross-reference 500 individual orders — the system does the math and produces actionable production documents.</p>

<h3>Delivery Management</h3>
<p>Multiple delivery strategies are supported — from basic driver assignment to optimized route planning to third-party fulfillment. Operators can offer pickup and shipping alongside delivery. The logistics infrastructure is designed to accommodate any regional delivery model, not just North American providers.</p>

<h3>Payment Infrastructure</h3>
<p>Each vendor connects their own payment account; Prepped takes its platform fee as a percentage of each charge. Payment coverage across 195+ countries and 135+ currencies means Prepped is viable in virtually every market where a vendor might operate.</p>

<h2>Competitive Position</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>vs. Shopify / Square Online</strong> — Handle ordering only. No production reports, no meal-selection subscriptions, no delivery coordination. Prepped covers the full operational lifecycle.</li>
  <li><strong>vs. CaterZen / FoodStorm</strong> — Enterprise catering software with enterprise pricing ($200–$500+/month plus setup fees). Prepped's pay-per-order model eliminates upfront risk and scales naturally with the business.</li>
  <li><strong>vs. HelloFresh / Blue Apron (vertically integrated)</strong> — These are meal kit brands, not platforms. They compete for the same customers a vendor serves; Prepped enables vendors to compete against them.</li>
  <li><strong>vs. Custom Development</strong> — Building ordering, subscriptions, production planning, and delivery management from scratch is a six-figure engagement. Prepped provides it at 3.5% per order with zero upfront cost.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Growth Strategy</h2>

<p>The meal prep industry grows as health-conscious consumers globally outsource food preparation. This trend is geographically uniform — Asia-Pacific meal kit delivery is growing at <strong>18.2% CAGR</strong> (Cognitive Market Research), making it the fastest-growing region globally. The GCC hospitality boom and expanding European catering market create additional high-growth vectors entirely independent of North American trends.</p>

<p>Prepped captures this growth through two channels: direct acquisition (operators searching for meal prep software find the platform through SEO and content marketing) and organic expansion (as vendors grow on the platform, Prepped's revenue grows proportionally through transaction fees). The zero-upfront-cost model eliminates the primary barrier to adoption in any market — a new meal prep business anywhere in the world can launch on Prepped with no capital investment beyond their food costs.</p>

<p>The platform's architecture — GCP global infrastructure, Cloudflare edge routing, Stripe's 195-country coverage, and timezone-aware scheduling — means international expansion is an operational decision, not an engineering one.</p>

